            "text": "Otters are carnivorous, semi-aquatic mammals known for their playful nature and expert swimming abilities. There are **13 different species** found across the globe, inhabiting everything from freshwater rivers and lakes to the open ocean.\n\n### Key Facts:\n*   **Family:** They are members of the **Mustelid** family, making them relatives of weasels, badgers, and wolverines.\n*   **Thick Fur:** Sea otters have the densest fur of any animal (up to 1 million hairs per square inch), which they use for insulation instead of blubber.\n*   **Diet:** They are active hunters that primarily eat fish, but they also consume crabs, mussels, and sea urchins.\n*   **Tool Use:** Sea otters are famous for being one of the few animals that use tools; they often use rocks to crack open shellfish while floating on their backs.\n*   **Social Life:** Some species are solitary, while others live in social groups. A group of otters resting in the water is called a **raft**.\n*   **Abilities:** They have streamlined bodies, webbed feet, and powerful tails. River otters can hold their breath for up to 8 minutes, while sea otters can dive to depths of over 300 feet.",
